 the region and about property in general. Property and ownership have special significance and carry specific meanings in Amazonia, which has been portrayed as the antithesis of Western, property-based, civilization. Through carefully constructed studies of land ownership, slavery, shamanism, spirit mastery, aesthetics, and intellectual property, this volume demonstrates that property relations are of central importance in Amazonia, and that the ownership of persons plays an especially significant role in native cosmology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aIndians of South AmericaxLand tenurezAmazon River Region. 0aIndians of South AmericaxMaterial culturezAmazon River Region. 0aLand tenurezAmazon River Region. 0aMaterial culturezAmazon River Region. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aaesthetics.  aamazonia.  aantithesis of western property based civilization.  acarefully constructed.  aclassic anthropological theme of property.  adetailed.  aethnography of amazonia.  aintellectual property.  aland ownership.  anative cosmology.  aownership of persons.  aproperty and ownership.  aproperty relations are central importance.  ashamanism.  aslavery.  aspirit mastery.1 aBonilla, Oiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrightman, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrightman, Marc, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCesarino, Pedro de Niemeyer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosta, Luiz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFausto, Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFausto, Carlos, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGor